oso) -- tChapter 21 1810–11 Piano Trio in B flat major, op. 97 (Archduke) -- tChapter 22 1812 Violin Sonata in G major, op. 96 -- tChapter 23 1815 Two Cello Sonatas, op. 102 -- tPart six 1816–27 -- tChapter 24 1815–24 The Late String Quartets – Context and Background -- tChapter 25 1824–5 String Quartet in E flat major, op. 127 -- tChapter 26 1825 String Quartet in A minor, op. 132 -- tChapter 27 1825 String Quartet in B flat major, op. 130 -- tChapter 28 1825–6 Grosse Fuge, op. 133 -- tChapter 29 1825–6 String Quartet in C sharp minor, op. 131 -- tChapter 30 1826 String Quartet in F major, op. 135 -- tAppendix 1 Early Chamber Music for Strings and Piano -- tAppendix 2 Variations -- tAppendix 3 Chamber Music for Wind -- tAppendix 4 Arrangements -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Beethoven’s Music by Opus Number -- tBeethoven Index -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis comprehensive survey shows how the larger scale works relate to Beethoven's chamber music and how the composer evolved an increasing freedom of form.Watson provides professional and amateur musicians, and music lovers generally, with a complete survey of Beethoven's chamber music and the background to each individual work - the loyalty of patrons, musicians and friends on theone hand; increasing deafness and uncertain health on the other. Attention is paid to the influence of such large-scale compositions as the Eroica Symphony and Fidelio on the chamber music of his middle years and theMissa Solemnis and the Ninth Symphony on his late quartets. The author examines Beethoven's ever-increasing freedom of form - largely a result of his mastery of improvisation and a powerful symbol of the fusion of classical discipline with the subversive spirit of romantic adventure which characterises his mature music. Beethoven's friends were not shy about asking him what his music meant, or what inspired him, and it is clear that he attached the greatest importance to the words he used when describing the character of his compositions. 'The tempo is more like the body,' he wrote when commending Malzel's invention of the metronome, 'but these indications of character certainly refer to the spirit.' ANGUS WATSON, a violinist and conductor, has been Director of Music at Stowe School, Winchester College and Wells Cathedral School, one of Britain's specialist music schools. From 1984-1989 he was Dean of Music at the newly founded Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChamber musiczGermanyy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChamber musiczGermanyy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAngus Watson.  aBeethoven's chamber music.  aEroica Symphony.  aFidelio.  aMissa Solemnis.  aNinth Symphony.  adeafness.  afreedom of form.  alarger scale works.  aloyalty of patrons.  amusicians.1 aCairns, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Angus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615909140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159091/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles